text: Going purely on the trailer (for now), this is actually really grating to watch. Not because "muh childhood" or anything, I'm welcome to adaptations if they're done well, because it introduces the originals to a new audience; it's more because it's another generic "CGI characters mess up a real humans life by being really annoying and stupid" plot but with characters who are so far removed from that it's kind of funny.  Granted, Beatrix Potter has some elements that could be considered a product of its time, so modernizing it a bit to be more relevant is fine, but you can do it without sucking out everything that made the characters and world so charming ("Paddington" found a good balance if I remember correctly). It's so jarring seeing a character who is known for being this naughty, but likeable kid surviving in the woods and thwarting a murderous gardener, throwing a frat-boy party and break dancing while acting like a douchebag.   Or it could just be that the trailer is awful, that's always an option.

text: The Peter Rabbit stories were a formative part of my childhood. They were written by a woman who gave her fortune away upon her death, and whose legacy was the preservation of England's lake country and respect for its wildlife. In what universe does this movie reflect anything Beatrix Potter wrote for or stood for?  'She felt passionately that all merchandise should remain faithful to her original book illustrations.' <- This is from the Potter biography on the OFFICIAL WEBSITE for Peter Rabbit. Whoever conceived of and greenlighted this gaslighting affront to turds everwhere should be ashamed of themselves. This movie has taken every element precious to Potter's books and to Potter herself, and done a hip little dance showing Peter's ass, on it. Literally - we get to watch it happen in the trailer.  Remember that story where Peter wasn't a child, but just an ageless scamp partying with a bunch of other animals, and there was a screaming contest with a human, with no sense of wonder, nature, peril, or childhood whatsoever - but it was really rendered well like that movie HOP? NEITHER DOES BEATRIX POTTER, BECAUSE SHE NEVER WROTE THE DAMN THING. NEVER WOULD HAVE.   --  Now for the one part that's tough to publish past YouTube.  Fuck you, Sony. Fuck right off.

text: Weird. I was just thinking during my lunch break last week: Why haven't they made a Peter Rabbit film?  Then I see this, hoping it'll be subtle, innocent, sophisticated and charming while teaching morals. My inner child is outraged.  And they fucked up by NOT getting James Cromwell to play Mr. McGregor. He would have been perfect -- the polar opposite to his kindly farmer in Babe. Instead they cast some spineless nebbish that will eventually team up with the animals to save his farm/get the girl etc. Why make him sympathetic? To shoehorn in a love story we don't need?  And apparently Mr. Tod is now an ally that parties with Peter? Rather than the diabolical yet charming villain who brawls with Tommy Brock?   TL;DR- Peter makes it rain lettuce, FUCK THIS MOVIE

text: Sony could have easily turned this into an amazing movie modeled after the heartwarming book. I mean, the story is already brilliant, so why crap all over it? The potential to bring this old story to a new generation was right there in their damn hands and they decided to modernize it to the point where you'd never know it takes after ANYTHING. I will not see this. I'm not saying it'll butcher my childhood, cuz it won't. That era of my life is over, so you can't destroy something  that doesn't exist anymore, no matter how much I loved the original story as a kid. However, I will say that they butchered an amazing opportunity and went with something that will be dated and no one will remember. Very unfortunate.

text: A year ago, 2 film directors made a drunk bet - one had to take the most evil character in literary history and make him lovable. The other had to take a lovable character and make everyone thoroughly despise him.  Director 2 chose Peter Rabbit. First, he got his 4 year old to write a script that mostly involves people screaming and running around. Second, he reimagined Peter as an irritating little twat. Yet somehow he still wasn‚Äôt quite hateable enough...  But one quick phone call to James Corden and his side of the wager was complete. Beatrix Potter‚Äôs been spinning so fast, she‚Äôs drilled her own rabbit hole to the centre of the earth.  (Incidentally, the cartoon version of Schindler‚Äôs List, with all the characters as animals, is released in December. You‚Äôll love Amon G√∂at - he‚Äôs so cute!! üêê)

text: I really feel like killing myself after watching this. What is wrong with today's animation studios? Especially Sony. There is no spirit anymore outside of Pixar, Disney or maybe Blue Sky. Sony is terrible as an animation company. Just look at the Emoji Movie. No spirit, no magic, no nothing. No original ideas either. And why does everybody need to feel that Peter Rabbit must be updated for today's kids? The Paddington movies kept the spirit of Michael Bond's book so well and that's why the character remains popular. The same with¬†The Snowman?¬†Peter Rabbit doesn't need fixing. The books still works well with today's youth. And¬†why can't they show the 1992 Peter Rabbit and Friends again? Which basically captured every little thing Peter Rabbit was about. Whoever allowed Sony to get the right to a Peter Rabbit movie needs their heads examined.

text: I know nostalgia glasses are powerful. I know that modernizing a story can work. I know that they can't follow the original beat for beat since books and movies are very different. Fine. I understand this, and I'm willing to be lenient. I don't remember the books of this very well, or the animated version, but, that said, WHY Sony? You, you can't REALLY think this is a good idea, tell me, TELL ME, that this is some sort of The Producers type scheme. Because that is the only way that this can work. Because this, this just looks like it's not just asking for something to go wrong. It's going up to fate's door, breaking it, breaking in and demanding for fate to fuck them over and for this to end horribly. I REALLY hope I'm wrong and this is better than it looks. But I get the feeling I'm not.

author: Aiden Cortez

text: I know I'm going to get a lot of flack for saying this, and I do agree that I think this trailer looks awful, and doesn't appeal to me. But let's get something straight: This movie is not intended for the fans who grew up with the source material. It's made for CHILDREN.   Sure, being a kids movie doesn't mean it's exempt from criticism, but I'm 100% sure that kids won't automatically pull out their pens and notebooks, and try to analyse what's good and bad about this movie. They likely won't extensively talk about the comedic timing, how immature the jokes were, and say "This ruined my childhood!" They will likely just sit in the movie theatre, watch it, and most likely enjoy it. And as long as kids like it, than the creators have done their job, and entertained their target audience.   Also, I'm pretty sure the world is doing just fine. The world isn't going to blow up just because of a terrible trailer.

text: I'm seeing a lot of people comment "You can't complain too much about these films, they're for kids", I have to counter argue this defence with these points:   1) The term "It's a kids' movie" can defend why a film isn't too violent or why it has a colourful art style, but it shouldn't be used to explain why a film is bad, children's films aren't immune from criticism and "It's a Kids' movie" isn't a license for a film to be lazy or uncreative.   2) The Default acceptable standard for children's movies shouldn't be "Whatever, it'll do, it's for kids", especially when there's so many children's movies out there that are both emotionally challenging and imaginative, from "Toy Story" to "The Secret of NIMH", "Matilda" to "The Neverending Story", there's no excuses for children's films to get away with being insultingly low standard or unambitious.    3) Children aren't the only audience who watch these films, don't forget that parents have to see them too, why should it be a chore or punishment for them? Give them an experience that they can appreciate with their kids, a bonding opportunity that they can sincerely share.   Great children's movies respect their young audience, they don't underestimate what kids can take in as an audience, they believe that kids are smarter than we think and try to teach them to understand storytelling values, they are so well written & produced that they can be treasured for a lifetime. Let's not shrug our shoulders or turn the other cheek when a film for kids is bad, we need to call them out on their low standards or easy pandering, because the next generation deserve movies that treat them with respect and don't just see them as a money making opportunity.
